  <data name="textBox1.Text" xml:space="preserve">
    <value>Welcome to Hookit!
This tool aims to assist in wrapping few types of objects.

The general flow is drag-n-drop objects into the "Input" text box.

Supported file extensions are: 

module wrapping: .dll, .exe
c++ class wrapping: , .txt, .h, .hpp, .i (visual studio intermediate files)
.i is recommended, see explanation further down.

The following are the supported types of objects:

* Dll and modules.
In this case, a wrapper dll code will be generated.
For the specific functions you want to examine you'll need to manually replace the passthrough functions implementations.

* source code.
An initial pass will run on the provided source code, and you will be presented with a check list of the found classes.
Check every class that you want a wrapper to be generated for it.

Since reading full C++ syntax is not a particulary easy task (and aboslutely outside the scope of this project),
and since specifically macro expansion code is very far from trivial,
i recommend building a project of your own that uses any of the classes you wish to wrap,
and setting the following the compiler flag "/P".
You can also set it manually by allowing "Preprocess to a file" in Visual Studio.
Visual Studio will generate ".I" (for intermediate) files instead of obj files.


Paste these files, or the text within those files into the Input section in Hookit.

Notice that obj files will not be created in that case, so revert it back after you've done it.

Credits:
The part that handles the dll wrapping isn't mine. I only fixed a small bug in it, and automated the process.
It was made by "Michael Chourdakis".
Here's the project location:
http://www.codeproject.com/Articles/16541/Create-your-Proxy-DLLs-automatically

The GUI Skin was taken from XCoolForm which was made by "Nedim Sabic".
You can take a look at it here: http://www.codeproject.com/Articles/33716/Fancy-Windows-Forms


Note:
A full class wrapping solution would probably have used gcc source code in order to read C++ syntax fully.
I do not have time for that, and this project was hacked in 2 days =)

Happy hacking!
Yoel Shoshan.
